div.p:
I am a foolish old woman, who am apt to speak what I think, and write as I feel; I am therefore always employed with my friends and correspondents either in committing errors or atoning for them. Your conduct has been so uniform, that I have fallen into fewer scrapes of this sort with you than any body else; you are not familiar with my absurdities, and there
fore it was, that this appeared so great to you;
some of my more experienced intimates would only have said—This is so like Dormer—and thought no more of it.

I told you so, Sir; I gave you other reasons;
I said it would not be agreeable nor conveni
ent to Sir George.
